      "type": "grammar",
      "title": "Basic Sentence Structure & Questions with 'Da li'",
      "explanation": "Serbian generally follows Subject-Verb-Object (SVO) word order, similar to English. However, because Serbian is a highly inflected language with grammatical cases, word order is more flexible than in English — you can rearrange words for emphasis without losing meaning. To form yes/no questions, Serbian uses the particle 'Da li' at the beginning of the sentence. For example, 'Govoriš srpski' (You speak Serbian) becomes 'Da li govoriš srpski?' (Do you speak Serbian?). In casual speech, you can also form questions simply by changing your intonation, just like in English. For 'where' questions, use 'Gde' (Где): 'Gde je banka?' (Where is the bank?).",
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "You speak Serbian. (statement)",
          "serbian_cyrillic": "Ти говориш српски.",
          "serbian_latin": "Ti govoriš srpski."
        },
        {
          "english": "Do you speak Serbian? (question)",
          "serbian_cyrillic": "Да ли говориш српски?",
          "serbian_latin": "Da li govoriš srpski?"
        },
        {
          "english": "Where is the bank?",
          "serbian_cyrillic": "Где је банка?",
          "serbian_latin": "Gde je banka?"
        },
        {
          "english": "How much does this cost?",
          "serbian_cyrillic": "Колико ово кошта?",
          "serbian_latin": "Koliko ovo košta?"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "cultural_note",
      "title": "Serbian Hospitality & Coffee Culture",
      "content": "Serbians are famous for their hospitality, and one of its most common expressions is the offering of coffee. When you visit a Serbian home, your host will almost certainly ask 'Hoćeš kafu?' (Would you like coffee?). Declining can be seen as impolite, so it is best to accept — even if you just take a few sips. Serbian coffee (srpska kafa / турска кафа) is a strong, unfiltered brew similar to Turkish coffee. It is prepared in a small pot called a 'džezva' and served in small cups. Coffee is not just a drink in Serbia — it is a social ritual. Friends meet for coffee for hours, and the phrase 'idemo na kafu' (let's go for coffee) is essentially an invitation to spend quality time together. In restaurants, do not be surprised if the waiter does not rush you; lingering over coffee is expected and encouraged."
    }
